segments.text: So the, what was the, after being in the Corps, was there the next internal, was it the band or the RVs or fish drill team that came up next?
It all came to a head with Melanie Sincrap in that trial because everything then was lumped in together as it related to women
And that's in the late 70s, because she graduates in May of 80.
Well, yeah, so it was probably mid-70s.
Why her?
How did she become the focus?
I really don't know.
And when I say I really don't know, I think it takes an individual that's really bitter about the manner in which they've been treated, I think, to go around cheating.
And I think she became very bitter about the manner in which the males treated her before.
And so her bitterness initially was her individual treatment.
She was in the Corps for years.

Now I understand, that's my way of saying I don't know for sure, I understand that her father and stepfather were both bird colonels, I think Air Force, and that her mother had a physical handicap, I think wheelchair bound, and I had heard that
The mother raised the daughter not to take no for an answer.
Don't let somebody put something over on you.
You keep plugging away.
Did you have any interaction with Melanie?
No.
In fact, she never did come to see me.
So you can't describe her by?
No.
Never did come in.
And that was one of the points that I made back at the trial, initially.
If someone was that embittered or had that much of a problem, why did they come to see me?
Of course, going back to what I said earlier about the Corps, about keeping everything within.
I think, I don't think that group of people at that time felt comfortable in going outside.
Anyone, male, female, whatever.
That changed over a period of time.
People would come visit with me about anything and everything, but not that group in the Corps back at that time.
Did the trial involving Melanie, did that occur while she was still a student?
Yes, it did.
And what was the decision?
The decision back at that time was against
The decision was made in favor of Melvin.
And if I'm not mistaken, that women could be members of all the organizations to include the band.
There was a financial settlement in regard to court costs and all.
I remember that it cost us a lot of money.
I remember that.
And my thought was that that was something we really didn't need to spend all that money on.
A federal court?
Uh-huh.
All right, let's go to the stage at Melanie's graduation.
Did you anticipate any incident?
Had you heard any?
None.
Had not heard anything at all.
And I was looking the other way.
I was not too far from you.
And I was not looking and I heard the almost like a stunned audience.
And had to ask someone who was sitting next to me what had happened.
And that's when I found out the jurors had not changed.
Right.

I was up on the front of the, let's put this in the tape, I was up on the front row in my dean of faculties duties normally after bringing the mace and putting it on the front, I would go to the back row and sit down.

After his speech that day, Lieutenant Governor Bill Hobby had motioned for me, as the diploma was being passed, I'd come up and he said, now when you get out to UT El Paso as the new president, stay in contact, maybe I can help.
And so we're just shooting the breeze, and I'm about to go back to my seat to get ready for the end of it, because I look and see there are only a few names left, and I hear a little bit of hissing.
And I said, oh my, good gracious.
And he said, what do you mean?
I said, well, there's some hissing.
That means somebody doesn't like something.
And I look to my right and see about one or two people away from coming up to get the diploma was Melanie Zingray.
He remembered her as having been, quote, a pain in the neck.
And he may have used some stronger words than that, because he said she had pestered him over and over.
And so we are right there when, as I recall, Dr. Miller says, no way I'm going to shake your hand.
And the whole audience then was kind of stunned.
All right, do you remember anything being said or done as we go back into the letterman's lounge?
I remember a couple of board members coming up to Jarvis saying, damn right, Jarvis, I wouldn't shake in her hand either.
She doesn't deserve to have her.
I normally, as I came back in, scooted out that back sliding door to scoot over.
And so I probably was right there when that was.
I normally walked out with a board member.
Because I sat in the front row always in what, third down or whatever, so there would have been a board member coming up the other side.
And I don't remember anybody saying anything to me going down the aisle and all the way back.
And then I just slipped out.
Did you hear anything in the next few days?
Did you hear any comments or anything?
Yeah, I heard the kind of comments you were talking about.
The number of people were saying, well, it's good that he didn't shake her hand.
She deserved it, et cetera.
Did you hear anybody giving Jarvis a hard time for not?
I didn't either.
All right, let's jump back in time now.
Let's go back.
And let's go to the, let's go back to the Williams years.
Mrs. Williams, describe her as the president's wife.
Margaret, she very strong as a person and had very strong feelings about everything.
And I'm not trying to hide it.
I don't remember the conversations that we had about specific things.
All I remember, though, no matter what it was, she would tell you how she felt about it.
And I know she was not too thrilled about board members who gave Dr. Williams a tough time.
She was very protective of Dr. Williams.
It was so before he had his heart attack and very much so afterwards.
So she was very protective.
Her life, her thoughts were about her kids, her family, hoping things would go well for them.
She was always cordial to me, always very nice, very pleasant.
I remember one time she came over and borrowed some peanut butter next door.
We enjoyed living next to them.
They were very private people.
Alright, let's go to his health.
Were you aware before his heart attack that that might be approaching?
Wasn't aware specifically in regard to
to Dr. Williams, although he had told me about his family before.
So I knew that there was a history of heart problems in his family.
But you never think about it as it relates to that specific individual and something was going to happen.
So I never really gave it much thought, other than the fact that I was aware.
Do you remember anything about
the evening it occurred, or how you first heard?
I was out at a golf course.
I was playing golf, and the word came out that he had been rushed to St. Joseph's.
Of course, I was playing at Briar Place, which was right here close by.
And I left the golf course and went up there.
Everything is fuzzy in my mind.
After that, I remember Nelda, and I remember Margaret, and the fact that he had had a massive heart attack.
And it happened in the afternoon?
Uh-huh.
It was Haskell, I think it was mid-afternoon, mid to late afternoon.
In the office?
I'm not sure where it was.
I don't remember that either.
I'm not sure where it was.
All I remember is I was on the golf course.
And you know, for some reason, that makes me think it's Saturday.
OK. And then he's taken to Houston.
and what little I remember is that we heard immediately that it was very, very serious.
Yeah, that's what I heard.
That's what they said to me.
And they didn't think he was going to make it.
Right.
I remember that.
I was in shock.
I just hadn't even thought about it.
And if I'm not mistaken, it was a number of weeks before he's back.
Describe him physically when you saw him after he came back.
He was really pale.
I remember that.
Looked like he had lost a lot of weight in the short period of time.
So much more subdued personality-wise.
Do you remember anything in his lifestyle before the heart attack that in hindsight might have contributed to it?
I don't remember smoking.
I don't remember his overdoing anything.
No.
Not a thing that would indicate it.
The only thing is his temper, his emotional competitiveness.
Let's see.
If you remember any, share some Williams anecdotes.
The funniest one to me was
I went to his office with a budget meeting.
One time in that long rectangular table that he had in his office, and Nella sat on one side, Dr. Williams was on the end, and I was on this side.
And we were talking about money.
And we were talking about a particular couple of figures.
And he multiplied something together.
And I laughed.
It wasn't even close.
Like he missed it by $180,000 or something.
And I said to him, you know, you only missed about $180,000.
That's not bad for a history major.
And he turned and he kicked me in the shin.
And I laughed.
But anyway, he, oh, you would always refer to your wife as being, you married...
She married the lower self.
I remember using that word.
In regard to administrative style, I would keep things in a folder and then I would schedule a time to go visit with them.
And then I would decide, after I walked into the office and sat down, whether it was going to be a social visit
we would handle a couple of minor things or we would get into major issues.

When he was in a bad mood, and a bad mood being something was bothering him for one reason or another, that he would just automatically be strongly in opposition to whatever it was that you were talking about.
So I learned administratively to decide what kind of mood he was in before
we ever got into issues.
As I said earlier, he was always very down to earth, no put on.
When he wasn't emotionally upset about something, would interact very well with you about whatever.
And he was so bright.
Go ahead.
I was going to say,
I always thought he had an almost endless file of good items to throw in a speech and so forth that those he had filed away.
Do you remember any major proposal that you tried to market to him that he didn't buy into?
I don't want to.
One of the, one of the, I'll always remember this one.
I went to see him about counseling center, personal counseling center.
And he let me know very quickly that any student, and those kinds of problems didn't need to be a student at Texas A&M.
And so I, over a period of time,
We discussed it and we eventually created the personal counseling center.
And that was something he was totally opposed to initially.
But again, his rationale was if they have that kind of a problem, that A&M wasn't the place that they ought to be.
And my argument was we have a lot of good kids.
carry a lot of baggage with them because of the families, the attention they had or not had as youngsters.
And when I came, that was one of the things I thought we needed very badly, right at the very beginning.
And I had told Wade Birch, Wade who had done a super job for me at East Texas, and I had hired Wade, that if I could create one here,
that I would want him to come down and get that one started.
And so that all came about.
And that was in 74 as well.
All right.
Do you remember any major ideas in student affairs that he introduced that you all used?
Well, it was one that we all used, I think,
Because we were all comfortable with it, but the fact that he brought those kids up there into his office, Ken Caperton and Roger, we thought that kids ought to be involved all over, all the time.
So it was something we all agreed to.
He had done it before I got here, so I felt more comfortable probably in doing so.
But we involved kids in everything.
And then I had the weekly meetings with the students and student leadership and we chatted.
He wanted to have some kind of relationship with them and we worked it out.
to where they had dinner, not dinner, but lunch once a month.
Remember that?
And it was my two groups that I had.
I had a Thursday night dinner with the executive committee of student building.
And then I had about 10 other major student leaders on the alderman for Thursday.
And so once a month for lunch, we'd bring those about 20 kids and we'd have lunch with about 20.
And then I would sit at the end
of the table and only be a resource.
It was his.
He sat in the middle, sort of like the Last Supper.
It's middle, and then the 20 would be around, and I'd be at the end.
So that was a way for him to have that interaction.
Describe his relation, Dr. Williams' relation with students and their reaction to him.
That first year, Randy Ross was student body president.
Randy just loved Dr. Williams.
And Randy's girlfriend at the time, Sandy, who was very actively involved, loved him too.
And they got married that summer after that first year that I was here.
And we flew with the Williams to San Antonio for the wedding.
But the...
He was very relaxed.
Some presidents, for some reason, get uptight around students, but he was very relaxed around students, and they appreciated that.
He was very honest with them, very frank, very friendly, and not paternalistic in any way, just a friendly, nice human being to the students, and they enjoyed that interaction, that relationship.
All right, how was he in dealing with paperwork?
Did the paper, was there a paper flow in and out or did things get lost?
Paper flow went fast and the, I'm sure Nelda was helpful with that.
I can remember I sent over talking about funny things.

all worked all of the fall, putting together all my ideas in regard to how I wanted to change things administratively, and so I had my secretary put all that together for me during the Christmas holidays, and I sent it to him right after we came back to school, starting in January.
Just before I sent it to him, I saw a cartoon in the newspaper, and the cartoon was one glob speaking to the other, and one glob was saying, I'm beginning to believe
that the meek will never inherit the earth.
I made a copy of that cartoon and I attached it to my proposal that I sent to him.
Sent that proposal over.
And I got a call from Nellie.
And Nellie said she heard Dr. Williams just laughing and beat a storm.
And she wondered what it was.
So she went in to see.
And he was looking at my cartoon.
So again, that was fun.
You could use humor as a part of even the administrative style.
But yeah, you never had to worry about waiting on things from Dr. Williams.
It was one way or the other.
quick response.
Did he have any pet peeves?
I think if anything it was people not being honest and direct with him.
That he wanted people to be honest and frank with him.
He couldn't stand pussyfooting around.
I think it was like paperwork and everything else.
You made a decision and you went on with things, and you just did the piddle and piddle and piddle.
Some of those things were driving crazy as it related to trying to catch the board in the right mood, in a good mood, to kind of push something through the board.
So that would bother him.
The kind of administrator you'd like to work for and with?
Let's see.
In those early years, do you remember any goals you had that, as you recall now, you weren't able to bring to reality?
No.

That first year and that proposal I sent forward, one of the things that I worked on at East Texas and thought it was important for us to do at that time was to have legal services available for students.
Gwen Flint, who was very actively involved with that, with me, and we got that approved.
Everything that we wanted to do and thought was important, he was helpful and supportive.
Now, you didn't get 35 staff members for every department,
We made some movement in every area, and he was very supportive in that regard.
And again, the support was providing services and programs for students, and that's what he wanted done, and that's what he wanted me to do, and he was very supportive of that.
Did you feel that the area under your administrative responsibility
was getting fair treatment compared to the rest of the campus?
Yes, without a doubt.
Tom Cherry was supportive and helpful.
John and you all in John's office.
John was very supportive and has always been supportive of me in regard to the things I was attempting to do.
So I never felt hindered in any way.
by the administrative staff or by the pros.
It was very important.
Let's go back then chronologically.
Dr. Williams has the heart attack, and then administratively, who took over his responsibilities, as you recall?
For me, the person who then contacted me about everything was Clyde Freeman.
Clyde was the one.
My assumption, though, was that...
Mr. Wells was the one that was really in charge, and that Clyde was doing his business for Clyde Wells.
Alright, did Mr. Wells physically come to the campus and take up office?
I didn't see him that way, but I heard that he did, and I heard he was here for lengthy periods of time in that office.
Alright, and then Dr. Williams comes back,
And then there is that board meeting where the board selects Dr. Miller as the new president.
Do you remember your first conversations with him, with Dr. Miller?
Early on, I remember I had never met him before.
And so it was the first meeting, and it was cordial.
It was interesting for me because at that time the University of Arkansas was courting me as a possibility for the Chief Student Affairs Officer at the University of Arkansas.
So as John did with Jarvis, I went to see Jarvis, set up an appointment, and told him that I wanted him to
to have whomever he wanted in that particular position
And if he did not, if he was not interested in having me in that position, that I had a couple options, and that I was willing to pursue those if he didn't want me in the position.
And so he, he told me he wanted me in that position, he wanted me to stay, and so I agreed to do so.
And I dropped that on the other way along.
Frank Broyles was on the committee, looking for, searching for the new Chief Student Affairs Officer.
And Frank Broyles called me, and
Fred Horsinger, the chief financial officer up there.
So they were both interested in, so I didn't tell them what I had done, but I called them back after I talked to them.
We were happy here.
Things had gone well.
Didn't think they were going to change in regard to going well.
And so I called them and told them.
Maribel and I had talked it over and discussed it.
We were happy here.
And I did want to be considered for the job.
Great.
organizationally, were there any changes when Jarvis became the president in student affairs?
We kept moving in the same direction that we had started in.
The only difference was that Malin came down from placement and became an assistant to Jarvis, which meant
We had someone right there in the office who we thought would be supportive.
But it didn't change in regard to how we operated.
Interestingly enough, administratively for me, Jarvis, never a time did I go to Jarvis's office and worry about how he was in terms of emotion.
I could always go ahead with whatever it was.
Jarvis blocked out the rest of the world and talked to me about anything and everything that we had on our agenda.
So whereas with Dr. Williams, you know, I'd have to pick and choose.
Timing this a little bit.
And by the way, I've told this to a few people, but I had a statistics problem.
It was just like Dr. Williams.

I loved him to death, but he would, if you asked the wrong question, when he was feeling bad, found out later that his problem was ulcers, and when he was feeling bad, he'd jump all over your fanny for asking a stupid question.
When he was in a good mood, you know, so it kind of reminded me of Dr. Williams, and then later, Frank Vandiver, same way.
The high highs and the low lows.
But with Jarvis, Jarvis was straight across.
So it just continued along.
Did the paper flow, getting a yes or a no answer, did that change much?
No.
For me, it was just the same.
And the frequency of being able to get to him and meetings of the key administrators continued at about the same rate?
Yep.
We probably had...
Jarvis started the breakfast with the key administrative staff.
Dr. Williams didn't have those.
And Dr. Williams didn't have many where he involved all the vice presidents.
He primarily related to each vice president on his own.
So the joint breakfast, that was a new thing with Jarvis.
Perry Atkinson,
By that time, had we gotten in the Howard Vest line?
Yeah, I think so.
Yeah.
And so we had breakfast.
And Walker, of course.
Yeah, Bob Walker.
So we had the breakfast.
And Mac.
And Mac.
Hi.
Let's go back and grab, who are the student leaders from those early years?
that deserve mention.
Steve Everhart, who was student body president the year after Randy Ross.
Give a brief little description of talents or achievements.
Steve was from New Chronicles.
He was significant for a number of reasons.
One, he went to Harvard Law School after he left here.
And then, bless his heart.
